According to the "Kotō Genealogy" (厚東氏系図), the clan originated from Mononobe no Moriya. It is said that his descendant Taketada established a residence in Tanai (modern-day {{ill|Ube, Yamaguchi|ja|宇部市|qq=draft}}, Yamaguchi Prefecture). During the Heian period, a figure named Mononobe Sukune Motoyo served as governor of Nagato, indicating the clan's early establishment in the region.

Initially, the Kotō Clan governed the eastern part of Asa District as local warriors but expanded their influence over time.

During the {{ill|Genpei War|ja|源平合戦|qq=draft}}, the clan initially supported the {{ill|Taira Clan|ja|平氏|qq=draft}} and participated in the {{ill|Battle of Ichi-no-Tani|ja|一ノ谷の戦い|qq=draft}}. However, they later sided with the {{ill|Minamoto Clan|ja|源氏|qq=draft}}. Their contributions at the {{ill|Battle of Dan-no-ura|ja|壇ノ浦の戦い|qq=draft}} earned them recognition, granting them dominion over the Asa District. The clan also participated in the {{ill|Mongol invasions of Japan|ja|元寇|qq=draft}} (1274 and 1281) alongside the {{ill|Ōuchi Clan|ja|大内氏|qq=draft}} under the orders of the {{ill|Kamakura Shogunate|ja|鎌倉幕府|qq=draft}}.

== Decline and Demise ==
The Kotō Clan’s decline began during its conflict with the Ōuchi Clan. After losing critical battles, including the {{ill|Battle of Shimo-furiyama|ja|霜降城|qq=draft}}, Kotō Yoshitake (義武) retreated to his holdings in {{ill|Kikuchi District|ja|企救郡|qq=draft}}, Buzen Province. Although a temporary truce with the Ōuchi Clan allowed the Kotō Clan to reclaim Nagato, their political power diminished. By 1362, the {{ill|Muromachi Shogunate|ja|Ashikaga Shogunate|qq=draft}} formally assigned the role of Nagato’s shugo to Ōuchi Hiroyo, marking the Kotō Clan’s effective downfall.

== List of Family Heads ==
1. {{ill|Kotō Taketada|ja|厚東武忠|qq=draft}}
2. {{ill|Kotō Takemoto|ja|厚東武基|qq=draft}}
...
17. {{ill|Kotō Yoshitake|ja|厚東義武|qq=draft}}

