The '''Kotō Clan''' (厚東氏) was one of the {{ill|Japanese clans|ja|日本の氏族|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese clans|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, centered in [[:en:Nagato Province|Nagato Province]] as local magnates and eventually serving as provincial [[:en:Shugo|shugo]] (military governors). The clan’s {{ill|honsei|ja|本姓|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/honsei|qq=}} (original family name) was [[:en:Mononobe clan|Mononobe]], and it claimed descent from [[:en:Mononobe no Moriya|Mononobe no Moriya]]. The Akiyoshi Clan, a branch family, traces its roots to Takeuji, the third son of the 11th head of the Kotō Clan.

== Overview ==
According to the "Kotō Genealogy" (厚東氏系図), the clan originated from Mononobe no Moriya. It is said that his descendant Taketada established a residence in Tanai (modern-day [[:en:Ube, Yamaguchi|Ube, Yamaguchi]], Yamaguchi Prefecture). During the Heian period, a figure named Mononobe Sukune Motoyo served as governor of Nagato, indicating the clan's early establishment in the region.

Initially, the Kotō Clan governed the eastern part of Asa District as local warriors but expanded their influence over time.

During the {{ill|Genpei War|ja|源平合戦|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Genpei War|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 治承・寿永の乱}}, the clan initially supported the [[:en:Taira clan|Taira Clan]] and participated in the [[:en:Battle of Ichi-no-Tani|Battle of Ichi-no-Tani]]. However, they later sided with the [[:en:Minamoto clan|Minamoto Clan]]. Their contributions at the [[:en:Battle of Dan-no-ura|Battle of Dan-no-ura]] earned them recognition, granting them dominion over the Asa District. The clan also participated in the [[:en:Mongol invasions of Japan|Mongol invasions of Japan]] (1274 and 1281) alongside the [[:en:Ōuchi clan|Ōuchi Clan]] under the orders of the [[:en:Kamakura shogunate|Kamakura Shogunate]].

== Decline and Demise ==
The Kotō Clan’s decline began during its conflict with the Ōuchi Clan. After losing critical battles, including the {{ill|Battle of Shimo-furiyama|ja|霜降城|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Battle of Shimo-furiyama|qq=}}, Kotō Yoshitake (義武) retreated to his holdings in {{ill|Kikuchi District|ja|企救郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kikuchi District|qq=}}, Buzen Province. Although a temporary truce with the Ōuchi Clan allowed the Kotō Clan to reclaim Nagato, their political power diminished. By 1362, the {{ill|Muromachi Shogunate|ja|Ashikaga Shogunate|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muromachi Shogunate|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} formally assigned the role of Nagato’s shugo to Ōuchi Hiroyo, marking the Kotō Clan’s effective downfall.

== List of Family Heads ==
1. {{ill|Kotō Taketada|ja|厚東武忠|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotō Taketada|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}
2. {{ill|Kotō Takemoto|ja|厚東武基|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotō Takemoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}
...
17. {{ill|Kotō Yoshitake|ja|厚東義武|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotō Yoshitake|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}

